<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-343-783  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 343 783.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  Feb 1989 v21 n2 p23(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tandem configurations for AGV systems offer simplicity andflexibility. (automated guided vehicle)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bozer, Yavuz A.; Srinivasan, Mandyam M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A demand for increasingly flexible and efficient automated guidedvehicle (AGV) systems has resulted in increasingly complicated andexpensive systems.andP;  In traditional AGV systems any vehicle canpick up or drop off items at any station.andP;  A new concept in AGVsystems is the tandem configuration, in which stations are dividedinto non-overlapping, single-vehicle closed loops.andP;  This systemcan be controlled by a less complicated control system,facilitates both central control and future expansion, andeliminates congestion.andP;  Its limitations include needing additionalspace and additional pick-up and drop-off points between adjacentloops and requiring balanced workloads.andP;  A load may have to behandled by several vehicles in order to reach its destination.andO;The throughput capacity should be comparable to traditionalsystems because of the reduction of congestion.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Materials HandlingFactory ManagementAutomationRobots.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Schematics of traditional and tandem AGV systems, layout forexample. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>